        "title": "Your Job Is Working Against You — Manage It",
        "body": "Dentistry locks you into sustained forward-head, rounded-shoulder posture for hours each day. This programme deliberately counters that with dead hangs, face pulls, band pull-aparts, and external rotations — but those only work if you treat them with the same intention as your main lifts. On clinic days, try to reset your posture every 60 minutes: stand, retract your shoulder blades, and take five deep breaths with your arms at your sides."
      },
      {
        "icon": "🍗",
        "title": "Protein Is the Non-Negotiable — Hit 160g Minimum",
        "body": "At 86 kg with a recomposition goal, you need at least 1.8–2.0 g/kg of protein daily — that is 155–170 g as a floor. This is the single dietary variable that most directly determines whether you lose fat while keeping muscle. Spread intake across four meals. If your current diet is not structured around protein targets, start by tracking protein alone for two weeks before worrying about total calories."
      },
      {
        "icon": "😴",
        "title": "Protect Your 7–8 Hours",
        "body": "Your sleep quality score of 7 and 7–8 hours duration are solid — do not let this slip as training intensity increases. Growth hormone release and muscle protein synthesis peak during deep sleep. If your stress pushes sleep below 7 hours consistently, reduce session RPE by one point that week rather than grinding through fatigue. Underrecovered training is worse than slightly easier training."
      },
      {
        "icon": "🎯",
        "title": "RPE Honesty Makes or Breaks This Block",
        "body": "An RPE 8 means two reps left in the tank, genuinely. If you are reaching failure on sets prescribed at RPE 7–8, the load is too heavy and you are accumulating fatigue that will compromise the next session. Start conservative in Week 1. The tempo prescriptions in this block — 3-second eccentrics on most compounds — will make moderate loads feel significantly harder than you expect."
      },
      {
        "icon": "🧱",
        "title": "Core Training Is Programmed — Do Not Add More",
        "body": "This block includes four dedicated core segments per week across anti-extension, anti-rotation, loaded flexion, and hanging work. That is a high dose. Do not add extra ab work on rest days or at the end of sessions — more volume does not accelerate ab visibility, and excessive core fatigue will compromise your squat and deadlift bracing. The abs will grow from this stimulus. The fat covering them will reduce from the deficit."
      },
